metadata.name: enter the dragon #11
metadata.description:
This generative token uses a modified fractal algorithm based on the Dragon Curve.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dragon_curve

Random colours and radius are used to visualize the pattern.


color scheme: 14 variations of sets of 4 colours
start angle: first direction, between 0 and 90
loops: how many iterations to pre-compute, between 7 and 15
angle: the angle of each turn, between 85 and 90
frames: total number of frames before the animation stops. Between 2500 and 5000.
alpha: alpha value used for some transparency. Between 200 and 250.

metadata.name: MoirÃ©_Ellipses_Dark #6
metadata.description:
This is a companion piece to https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/3831 - MoirÃ©_Ellipses_Light. There's little difference between the two aside from palette choice, and variation is somewhat limited.

Between four and six elliptical rings rotate in alternately contrary directions. Each ellipse is bounded within by a further ellipse, and between these two points, striations are marked at a slight angle. The resulting motion produces emergent MoirÃ© patterns.

The number of ellipses, their segmentation level and colour are all generated from hash. The eccentricity of the inner and outer ellipses is also hash-generated, resulting in uniquely beautiful images.

This version features lighter hues and a darker background.

metadata.name: rememberance #15
metadata.description:
A field of slit-scan flowers, created from slicing images from my "abstracted expressions" acrylic painting/collage series, minted on exchange.art ( https://exchange.art/series/abstracted%20expression/nfts ). I have been looking for a way to bridge my code-based art on Tezos with my physical art on Solana, and this is an attempt to do so. 

The 9 paintings used in the piece are all acrylic, charcoal, wax pastel, and collage on paper, scanned at 600dpi. The FxHash mint is coded in p5.js

metadata.name: Coded Cosmos #11
metadata.description:
At the edge of the universe, a powerful entity kick-starts the accretion of a future planet.  The humanoid entity is a builder of worlds who channels a cosmic energy, commanding it to bring into being a primitive form.  From dust, the entity makes rock, then mountains, then . . . a world.

The planetâ€™s birth will be quick, but its future will extend into the eons to bring forth other entities, who may, one day, seek out dust at the edge of its universe to begin the cycle anew.

Coded cosmos is an exquisitely designed spacescape created using p5.js.  Several systems are married into layers of:
- multicolored stars.
- recursive clouds of gas and dust.
- a richly textured planet circled by thousands of thoughtfully distributed asteroids.
- a conglomerated asteroid in the foreground.
- a randomly posed, articulated, generative figure.
- Perlin light rays and flow field electric arcs.

All iterations contain a star field, planet, clouds and asteroids.  Randomly selected iterations may contain:
- a randomly posed, generative figure.
- a conglomerated asteroid in the foreground.
- Perlin light rays along the figureâ€™s vertical axis.
- flow field electric arcs extending from the center of the figure.
- Bonus edition: a red planet (1:100).

To save any frame as a 1990x1080 png, press the Down Arrow.
To toggle full screen mode, click or tap the canvas area.

Created using p5.js with popular coding examples: perlin noise, flow fields and vectored ellipses, along with proprietary color palettes, stochastic procedures and other proprietary code by Ed Cavett.
